         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">

<ab><lb n="1"/>  <persName type="emperor"><w>Αὐτοκράτορα</w>  <lb n="2"/><name nymRef="#Νέρβα"><hi rend="ligature">Νέ</hi>ρβαν</name>    <g ref="#leaf"/>  <name nymRef="#Καῖσαρ">Καίσα  <lb n="3" break="no"/>ρα</name>  <g ref="#arabesque"/>  <w lemma="σεβαστός">Σεβαστὸν</w></persName><lb n="4"/><w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w>  <w lemma="δῆμος">δῆμος</w>  <w lemma="ἐκ">ἐκ</w>  <w lemma="ὁ">τῶν</w>  <lb n="5"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Διογένης">Διογένους</name>    <g ref="#stop"/>  <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w>  <lb n="6"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μένανδρος">Μενάνδρου</name>    <space extent="3" unit="character"/>  <lb n="7"/><w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Διογένης">Διογένους</name></persName></persName></persName>  <lb n="8"/><w>νεωτέρου</w>    <space extent="3" unit="character"/>  <lb n="8a"/></ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Imperator Nerva Caesar Augustus. The People (put up his statue) from the (funds) of Diogenes the younger, son of Menandros, son of Diogenes.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This base is approximately a pair with <ref type="iAph" target="">1292</ref> (=83.75) (dedication to Hadrian). A further dedication from the same building, to Antoninus Pius (<ref type="iAph" target="">1300</ref>=80.24) is a little different in style. Were all these among the <foreign xml:lang="grc">τειμαὶ Σεβαστῶν</foreign> claimed by Diogenes, who built the gate? If so, he was precipitate in claiming to have dedicated them. Should the Nerva be taken to be as late as the latest in the group? If so, which - Antoninus Pius?</p>
            <p>Diogenes the Younger also appears in <ref type="iAph" target="">1254</ref>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
